00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:02.730
And I did that my whole life.

00:32:02.730 --> 00:32:05.660
That's how I learned how
to do things in the world.

00:32:05.660 --> 00:32:07.450
I never went to college.

00:32:07.450 --> 00:32:10.069
I own a snowboard
outerwear company in Japan.

00:32:10.069 --> 00:32:12.110
I've dealt with all my
contracts in snowboarding,

00:32:12.110 --> 00:32:13.520
never had an agent.

00:32:13.520 --> 00:32:17.420
And so I've just taken on
things where the level of risk

00:32:17.420 --> 00:32:20.570
feels high, but I'm
willing to fail.

00:32:20.570 --> 00:32:24.230
And that's one of my key
understandings on risk.

00:32:24.230 --> 00:32:27.770
If you're willing to
fail, you can always

00:32:27.770 --> 00:32:31.700
gain something from it because
I've failed many times.

00:32:31.700 --> 00:32:32.940
I always do.

00:32:32.940 --> 00:32:35.270
It's something that
I'm expected to do.

00:32:35.270 --> 00:32:38.160
And people forget
that, I realize,

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:39.830
especially when I
get someone coming

00:32:39.830 --> 00:32:41.670
wanting to build a tiny home.

00:32:41.670 --> 00:32:44.160
They have these prints
of, like, all these plans

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:46.221
they've been planning
out for years

00:32:46.221 --> 00:32:47.720
and they've never
picked up a hammer

00:32:47.720 --> 00:32:51.200
yet because they're scared
something's going to go wrong.

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:54.500
And I try to encourage
people the level of risk,

00:32:54.500 --> 00:32:58.280
of it being known as failure.

00:32:58.280 --> 00:33:00.670
It's kind of like,
give it a shot.

00:33:00.670 --> 00:33:03.260
If you need to do
it on a small level,

00:33:03.260 --> 00:33:06.470
do that, and just learn
from the failing process

00:33:06.470 --> 00:33:08.332
because those have the answers.

00:33:08.332 --> 00:33:10.790
And it's not going to be an
answer that you're looking for.

00:33:10.790 --> 00:33:13.420
It's going to be something
that you're not expecting.

00:33:13.420 --> 00:33:15.211
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
ask you of the moment

00:33:15.211 --> 00:33:16.937
when you jump up to
the helicopter, what

00:33:16.937 --> 00:33:18.770
do you think that
[INAUDIBLE] more concerned

00:33:18.770 --> 00:33:19.970
about the jump itself?

00:33:19.970 --> 00:33:21.360
Or maybe about the picture?

00:33:21.360 --> 00:33:22.870
Or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:33:25.644 --> 00:33:27.310
MIKE BASICH: That
photo, the helicopter,

00:33:27.310 --> 00:33:29.570
was a unique one for me.

00:33:29.570 --> 00:33:32.620
My biggest issue at the
moment before I jumped

00:33:32.620 --> 00:33:36.280
was a down pressure of the
blades of the helicopter.

00:33:36.280 --> 00:33:39.580
So I actually got going
faster than gravity.

00:33:39.580 --> 00:33:42.370
I could barely lift my
board off this skid.

00:33:42.370 --> 00:33:44.080
I just kind of slid off.

00:33:44.080 --> 00:33:47.570
And around that time, I totally
forgot about the remote,

00:33:47.570 --> 00:33:49.840
that I was shooting photos.

00:33:49.840 --> 00:33:52.570
And there's a
certain process when

00:33:52.570 --> 00:33:55.420
that's happened because
when I grab my snowboard,

00:33:55.420 --> 00:33:58.730
the other hand naturally
wants to do the same.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:00.720
And so I had no idea
if I took the photo.

00:34:00.720 --> 00:34:02.790
This is back in the
slide film days,

00:34:02.790 --> 00:34:06.649
so I just knew the camera
took the whole roll.

00:34:06.649 --> 00:34:08.440
And I was lucky enough
to get a photo of it

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:11.139
because I put
myself in a position

00:34:11.139 --> 00:34:13.420
where I didn't want the
pressure from other film

00:34:13.420 --> 00:34:14.590
and photographers.

00:34:14.590 --> 00:34:17.620
So I was the only one
there taking a photo.

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:22.760
And it became larger than
I thought it would be.

00:34:22.760 --> 00:34:25.810
But in the perspective of
being on the top looking down,

00:34:25.810 --> 00:34:29.440
it was something I felt. I
waited while until I felt

00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:32.920
that zone like clarity, like
this is what we want to do

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:33.736
and I see it.

00:34:33.736 --> 00:34:34.610
It's going to happen.

00:34:34.610 --> 00:34:35.464
And here I go.

00:34:35.464 --> 00:34:36.880
AUDIENCE: So in a
way, you've been

00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:40.449
a pioneer of marrying
the sport and photography

00:34:40.449 --> 00:34:43.070
that you did when you started.

00:34:43.070 --> 00:34:46.270
So you've seen as far as some
sort of unexplored territory

00:34:46.270 --> 00:34:49.050
that not a lot of
riders are looking into.

00:34:49.050 --> 00:34:51.580
Like, in a way,
you are 25 or 30,

00:34:51.580 --> 00:34:54.230
right, when you starting doing
this personal photography?

00:34:54.230 --> 00:34:57.550
What is the creative,
unexplored territory today

00:34:57.550 --> 00:35:00.910
that you would have done
if you had to be completely

00:35:00.910 --> 00:35:03.130
creative [INAUDIBLE]?

00:35:03.130 --> 00:35:04.630
MIKE BASICH: I think
the key element

00:35:04.630 --> 00:35:07.810
to that is knowing less.

00:35:07.810 --> 00:35:11.390
I was able to shoot
cameras in a way

00:35:11.390 --> 00:35:13.780
because I didn't know
anything about them.

00:35:13.780 --> 00:35:16.790
And so I kind of twisted
the rules a little bit

00:35:16.790 --> 00:35:19.690
because I wasn't taught.

00:35:19.690 --> 00:35:22.790
I just kind of took
it in a raw space.

00:35:22.790 --> 00:35:27.725
And so I think it's important
to learn about things.

00:35:27.725 --> 00:35:30.350
And what I've learned, if you're
going to learn about something

00:35:30.350 --> 00:35:32.410
and want to be in a
new space with it,

00:35:32.410 --> 00:35:35.980
creative-wise and
innovative-wise,

00:35:35.980 --> 00:35:38.680
is to go back to
that discomfort,

00:35:38.680 --> 00:35:41.230
crossing the threshold,
letting go of everything

00:35:41.230 --> 00:35:45.220
you know, and just kind
of like take a risk

00:35:45.220 --> 00:35:47.020
on putting something
together that

00:35:47.020 --> 00:35:49.270
has a lot to do with
timing and where

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:51.400
technology is at the moment.

00:35:51.400 --> 00:35:55.450
Because what's happened with me
is technology met some ideas.

00:35:55.450 --> 00:35:58.610
Some took 10 years,
some took weeks.

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:01.240
But they all kind of
were a moment in time

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:03.400
that wasn't together yet.

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:05.260
And I look outside
of snowboarding

00:36:05.260 --> 00:36:10.090
a lot, outside of photography a
lot, at different technologies.

00:36:10.090 --> 00:36:12.910
The drone world-- soon as
I saw something happen,

00:36:12.910 --> 00:36:16.430
I realized I don't need
a paraglider anymore.

00:36:16.430 --> 00:36:20.290
I don't know how a camera's
going to mount on a drone yet,

00:36:20.290 --> 00:36:24.100
because they're too heavy,
but four or five years later,

00:36:24.100 --> 00:36:26.060
it finally happened.

00:36:26.060 --> 00:36:27.790
And so that's kind
of in a simple way

00:36:27.790 --> 00:36:30.490
of a different equation
from different industries

00:36:30.490 --> 00:36:33.420
coming together to do
something together.

00:36:33.420 --> 00:36:35.890
SPEAKER 1: I guess I have a
few more questions as well.

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:37.829
One of the questions
is where Google--

00:36:37.829 --> 00:36:38.620
I work for YouTube.

00:36:38.620 --> 00:36:40.990
I'm an engineer on YouTube.

00:36:40.990 --> 00:36:45.850
What's going on with your
YouTube channel right now?

00:36:45.850 --> 00:36:47.440
MIKE BASICH: Not much.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:50.950
I, for some reason,
don't spend a lot of time

00:36:50.950 --> 00:36:52.720
on my YouTube channel.

00:36:52.720 --> 00:36:56.140
I don't know if it's because
I'm unfamiliar with it.

00:36:56.140 --> 00:37:00.460
I probably blame some of that
on the edits that come out.

00:37:00.460 --> 00:37:02.860
I've handed over the
footage to someone else

00:37:02.860 --> 00:37:06.820
and they keep their edits
on their YouTube channels.

00:37:06.820 --> 00:37:11.020
And so that's kind
of what I've learned

00:37:11.020 --> 00:37:12.430
a little bit in my photography.

00:37:12.430 --> 00:37:14.380
I've sat down and
edited my own things,

00:37:14.380 --> 00:37:18.010
but I have more coverage, more
marketability if I hand it

00:37:18.010 --> 00:37:21.760
over to somebody and they can
do something else with it.

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:24.640
And so I don't have a lot of
control over all the videos

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:27.130
to put on my
YouTube is one part.

00:37:27.130 --> 00:37:30.147
SPEAKER 1: Do you edit all
of your own content as well?

00:37:30.147 --> 00:37:31.480
MIKE BASICH: I do on some level.

00:37:31.480 --> 00:37:37.080
I used to do it a lot, but
it's the quality, everything--

00:37:37.080 --> 00:37:38.360
I'm on the road so much.

00:37:38.360 --> 00:37:41.290
I can only do so
much with my laptop.

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:44.320
Everything else is too
much for me to handle,

00:37:44.320 --> 00:37:46.240
so I usually just
hand things off

00:37:46.240 --> 00:37:47.923
because I'm bouncing
around a lot.

00:37:47.923 --> 00:37:48.770
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:37:48.770 --> 00:37:52.120
That's the easy way to do it.

00:37:52.120 --> 00:37:55.217
What awesome technologies
are you kind of looking for,

00:37:55.217 --> 00:37:56.800
that you've seen in
the news or you've

00:37:56.800 --> 00:37:58.591
seen other companies
working on that you're

00:37:58.591 --> 00:38:02.090
really excited about that
might influence your work?

00:38:02.090 --> 00:38:08.400
MIKE BASICH: Oh, I'm not
totally pinpointed on,

00:38:08.400 --> 00:38:10.260
like, the circle camera.

00:38:10.260 --> 00:38:15.090
I've seen that get invaded
into a little ball now.

00:38:15.090 --> 00:38:18.949
So I'm kind of curious on
where that perspective goes.

00:38:18.949 --> 00:38:21.240
Sometimes I worry that it's
getting farther and farther

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:24.130
away from us
learning how to feel

00:38:24.130 --> 00:38:28.170
the experience, that there's a
bigger gap in the actual action

00:38:28.170 --> 00:38:30.910
part of the self doing it.

00:38:30.910 --> 00:38:35.610
And so that's one thing that
when you look at a screen,

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:37.719
I get a little worried if
the kids watching this,

00:38:37.719 --> 00:38:39.510
that they're going to
actually go and do it

00:38:39.510 --> 00:38:40.895
or if that's just enough.

00:38:40.895 --> 00:38:41.520
SPEAKER 1: Yeah

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:42.686
MIKE BASICH: Because we're--

00:38:42.686 --> 00:38:45.390
technology-wise, it's
becoming more and more real,

00:38:45.390 --> 00:38:47.220
like that you're actually there.

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:48.470
And that's making.

00:38:48.470 --> 00:38:52.110
I think, the younger
generation just--

00:38:52.110 --> 00:38:53.820
that's cool, that's it.

00:38:53.820 --> 00:38:56.020
They don't have the
desire to go do it.

00:38:56.020 --> 00:38:59.060
So I'm hoping somewhere
in the mix of technology

00:38:59.060 --> 00:39:02.040
in days to come,
that it'll bring

00:39:02.040 --> 00:39:06.490
us into a more of a
feeling it ourselves.

00:39:06.490 --> 00:39:10.930
SPEAKER 1: Do you kind of look
at VR as an extension of that?

00:39:10.930 --> 00:39:14.510
So it'll make kids
passive and accepting of,

00:39:14.510 --> 00:39:17.470
oh, I did it in VR, so I don't
need to do it in real life.

00:39:17.470 --> 00:39:20.100
MIKE BASICH: I-- no.

00:39:20.100 --> 00:39:21.990
I don't.

00:39:21.990 --> 00:39:26.160
What I do see it doing is being
a teaching-- if somebody wants

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:28.350
to learn how to do
a trick, I think

00:39:28.350 --> 00:39:30.210
it could help them
visualize what

00:39:30.210 --> 00:39:32.090
it is to do a double backflip.

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:34.170
So they get to see something.

00:39:34.170 --> 00:39:37.290
But the simpleness of just,
say, snowboarding, just

00:39:37.290 --> 00:39:41.020
going down a hill, I
think, does the opposite.

00:39:41.020 --> 00:39:44.130
It brings a person farther
away from doing a sport.

00:39:44.130 --> 00:39:49.590
And I've learned-- my niece
actually has scoliosis

00:39:49.590 --> 00:39:53.070
and she's doing some
major exercises that

00:39:53.070 --> 00:39:54.360
are very painful.

00:39:54.360 --> 00:39:57.270
And the VR has
actually been very pain

00:39:57.270 --> 00:40:01.530
relieving because it makes your
mind disconnect from your body

00:40:01.530 --> 00:40:04.440
on some level because you're
in this other world, of course.

00:40:04.440 --> 00:40:06.650
That's kind of the idea.

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:10.080
So I see a huge
outlet for people

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:13.530
to be released from
struggles or just

00:40:13.530 --> 00:40:17.250
taking a break from life or
gain through a certain exercise

00:40:17.250 --> 00:40:19.925
and getting progressive with.

00:40:19.925 --> 00:40:21.300
SPEAKER 1: So what
happens if you

00:40:21.300 --> 00:40:24.920
were to use VR when you're
living off the grid?

00:40:24.920 --> 00:40:26.820
MIKE BASICH: Oh, I
had someone come out

00:40:26.820 --> 00:40:30.600
and we filmed the full VR video.

00:40:30.600 --> 00:40:33.030
And for me, it's a
little-- it's hard

00:40:33.030 --> 00:40:35.940
because I'm there all the
time, then I watch something

00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:37.539
and it's different.

00:40:37.539 --> 00:40:40.080
You feel like you didn't get to
tell the whole story that you

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:41.110
wanted to tell.

00:40:41.110 --> 00:40:43.290
And this has happened
in my whole career.

00:40:43.290 --> 00:40:46.440
People take their own stories
on when they see a certain image

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:48.240
or video.

00:40:48.240 --> 00:40:55.710
And the VR, I think, is it's
a three dimension, gives you

00:40:55.710 --> 00:40:59.310
something back to
losing yourself,

00:40:59.310 --> 00:41:00.810
which I think is a plus.

00:41:00.810 --> 00:41:03.060
But too much, I wonder.

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:06.570
Like, it's less
being in the world.

00:41:06.570 --> 00:41:09.120
In some ways, we're
creating a world.

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:11.000
So I kind of--

00:41:11.000 --> 00:41:11.570
I don't know.

00:41:11.570 --> 00:41:14.310
I challenge you on
where we're going

00:41:14.310 --> 00:41:16.710
to go with that
because in some ways,

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:19.770
we're all responsible
for what happens.

00:41:19.770 --> 00:41:23.500
Each generation is
born into groundwork.

00:41:23.500 --> 00:41:25.830
And so the next
generation is going

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:30.270
to think VR is just the
standard, which it probably

00:41:30.270 --> 00:41:32.370
will become a standard.

00:41:32.370 --> 00:41:35.370
But no one's really, as
generation comes on, they never

00:41:35.370 --> 00:41:38.450
ask, could we do it different?

00:41:38.450 --> 00:41:41.520
They're just kind of
like, it's already set.

00:41:41.520 --> 00:41:43.800
Progress with it,
but maybe there's

00:41:43.800 --> 00:41:46.400
a moment where someone
should have said, no.

00:41:46.400 --> 00:41:47.900
If you're going to
do this, you need

00:41:47.900 --> 00:41:49.691
to at least go outside
and stick your hands

00:41:49.691 --> 00:41:51.179
in the dirt for five minutes.

00:41:51.179 --> 00:41:52.470
Just remember that you're here.

00:41:52.470 --> 00:41:54.840
SPEAKER 1: Switching gears,
I wanted to ask about this.

00:41:54.840 --> 00:41:57.100
So you didn't go
over this at all,

00:41:57.100 --> 00:41:59.060
but you build your
own ski lift, right?

00:41:59.060 --> 00:42:01.710
Like, on your property, out
in the middle of nowhere,

00:42:01.710 --> 00:42:03.280
with your hands.

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:05.200
Can you talk a little
bit about that?

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:06.570
MIKE BASICH: Yeah.

00:42:06.570 --> 00:42:12.200
That pushed my
engineering ability a lot.

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:15.270
Yeah I came across this
old chairlift from Sweden.

00:42:15.270 --> 00:42:16.260
It was in pieces.

00:42:16.260 --> 00:42:19.020
And I had a tow rope for
years at my property,

00:42:19.020 --> 00:42:21.540
so I was like, oh, this is
perfect, to get off the ground

00:42:21.540 --> 00:42:23.690
and bury anything.

00:42:23.690 --> 00:42:28.350
And it wasn't so
much of something

00:42:28.350 --> 00:42:32.880
I had a long-term goal of,
but I love progressing.

00:42:32.880 --> 00:42:35.100
My mind is always busy so
I'm trying to find a place

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:37.140
to put it to action.

00:42:37.140 --> 00:42:40.500
So this was something that
got me an understanding of how

00:42:40.500 --> 00:42:44.220
the engineering of physics
work because I am not

00:42:44.220 --> 00:42:45.450
very good at schooling.

00:42:45.450 --> 00:42:49.020
I'm just great on
hand and back to I

00:42:49.020 --> 00:42:53.410
was willing to take the risk of
whatever this was going to be.

00:42:53.410 --> 00:42:54.690
And I learned a lot.

00:42:54.690 --> 00:42:59.520
It's fascinating, engineering
of what happens on a chairlift.

00:42:59.520 --> 00:43:04.039
300 pounds becomes 12,000
pounds within seconds.

00:43:04.039 --> 00:43:05.580
SPEAKER 1: But you
were never worried

00:43:05.580 --> 00:43:08.164
that you were going to fall off
or it was going to break or--

00:43:08.164 --> 00:43:09.080
MIKE BASICH: Oh, yeah.

00:43:09.080 --> 00:43:09.746
SPEAKER 1: Yeah.

00:43:09.746 --> 00:43:11.790
MIKE BASICH: Yeah.

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:14.730
SPEAKER 1: I guess the drop
was less than the 30 meters

00:43:14.730 --> 00:43:15.720
from the helicopter.

00:43:15.720 --> 00:43:18.095
MIKE BASICH: Yeah, it was
rocks, so it's a little harder.

00:43:18.095 --> 00:43:21.510
But I had a bunch
of friends help out.

00:43:21.510 --> 00:43:24.157
And some never came
back, some stuck

00:43:24.157 --> 00:43:25.240
through the whole process.

00:43:25.240 --> 00:43:26.820
Took about eight months.

00:43:26.820 --> 00:43:29.100
And I didn't have
any fancy equipment,

00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:33.930
so a lot of cowboy just putting
ropes up the trees with winches

00:43:33.930 --> 00:43:37.380
because we lifted six towers.

00:43:37.380 --> 00:43:40.620
And drawing a straight line
in mid air up the mountain

00:43:40.620 --> 00:43:43.692
is pretty challenging to
figure out how to do that.

00:43:43.692 --> 00:43:44.400
SPEAKER 1: Right.

00:43:44.400 --> 00:43:46.830
MIKE BASICH: So it was fun
working with old school

00:43:46.830 --> 00:43:50.490
equipment and
figuring that all out.

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:53.080
SPEAKER 1: I'm kind of curious
about your shopping habits.

00:43:53.080 --> 00:43:54.960
This is weird
question, but so you

00:43:54.960 --> 00:43:57.930
said you think a lot
about what you're

00:43:57.930 --> 00:44:01.560
going to buy before you bring
it back home because there's

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:05.100
effort involved in both
bringing it there and taking

00:44:05.100 --> 00:44:06.411
the rubbish away.

00:44:06.411 --> 00:44:07.410
MIKE BASICH: Yeah, yeah.

00:44:07.410 --> 00:44:08.820
